<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802162694 </F>
<F P=103> PA0802162694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Venezuelan economic developments monitored through 8 
February. 
  Colombia's International Sugar and Molasses Marketing 
Company 
purchased the Urena Sugar Mill for 320 million bolivares. The 
transaction was conducted at the Venezuelan Investment Fund 
(FIV) offices. FIV President Nelson Rivera stated the 
transaction was beneficial for the country because the 
investment and expenditures incurred throughout the sale process 
were recovered. (Caracas Venezolana de Television in Spanish 
2350 GMT 27 Jan 94) 
  The Venezuelan Central Bank (BCV) has reported that, owing 
to 
a reduction in oil revenues, Venezuela's international reserves 
dropped by $744 million last January and now total $11.912 
billion. According to the BCV, another factor contributing to 
the decline is the climate of mistrust that exists in the 
financial market in the wake of the government's intervention in 
Banco Latino. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2234 GMT 3 Feb 94) 
  Venezuela foreign debt bonds have been hurt by a decrease in 
value of U.S. long-term bonds. The par bond fell one point to 
70.75 due to U.S. 30-year bond sales. In addition, investors 
have adopted a cautious stance as they are waiting to see what 
specific measures President Rafael Caldera will take. (Caracas 
EL NACIONAL in Spanish 4 Feb 94 p E-1) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

