<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister May Delay German Visit Until Nuclear Treaty Signed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0902153494 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 7 
Feb 94 p A8 </F>

<F P=103> PY0902153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- Foreign Minister Celso Amorim may 
postpone his trip to Germany, which was scheduled for the end of 
the month, following the delay by the Senate in ratifying 
international agreements on nuclear safeguard. O ESTADO has 
learned that the minister is not willing to be questioned by the 
German Government, which conditions participation in programs 
including the transfer of high technology to Brazilian 
guarantees that it will use nuclear energy only for peaceful 
purposes. 
  The Senate Foreign Affairs Committee must ratify amendments 
to the Tlatelolco Treaty and to the quadripartite agreement 
signed between Brazil, Argentina, the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) and the Brazilian-Argentine Agency for 
Accounting and Control (ABACC). After months of negotiations, 
Senator Dirceu Carneiro (Brazilian Social Democracy Party - 
Santa Catarina), who coordinates the Committee's project for 
nuclear safeguard, endorsed on 3 February amendments to the text 
of the quadripartite agreement for the supervision of nuclear 
research in Brazil. The text, however, was not voted on for 
lack of quorum. There will probably be no quorum in the next 
meeting of the Committee, which will take place on 10 February, 
one day before the Carnival weekend begins. 
  Foreign Minister Amorim has not officially confirmed if he 
will postpone his trip. He admitted on 4 February, however, 
that he would like to continue negotiations with the German 
Government. He said: "It would be much better if I could take 
with me two ratified accords. Instead of being questioned about 
them, we would be free to begin talks about scientific 
cooperation and access to technology," adding: "I believe 
Congress is fulfilling its duty and analyzing the texts." The 
minister admitted that Germany may be "concerned" about possible 
consequences of a delay in ratifying these agreements. 
"Nonetheless, Germany is aware that the delay is not caused by 
lack of interest," he said. 

</TEXT>

