<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   D. Ortega Recognizes Clinton for Lifting Vietnam Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902161694 Managua Canal Cuatro Television in Spanish 0300 
GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0902161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Canal Cuatro Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Extravision" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Former President Daniel Ortega recognized the 
decision of U.S. President Bill Clinton to suspend the trade 
embargo on Vietnam that had been in effect since 1975 and called 
on the U.S. President to follow suit with the people of Cuba. 
  [Begin Ortega recording] What has happened? Despite the 
embargo and the blockade, Vietnam continued to grow and develop. 
Finally, in an intelligent and courageous measure -- we must 
recognize this -- U.S. President Bill Clinton decided to lift 
the trade embargo on Vietnam. We are now sending a message to 
President Clinton telling him that we recognize his courageous 
action of bringing justice to the Vietnam case because U.S. 
policy was unfair as long as the embargo and blockade were 
maintained. 
  We recognize President Clinton's courageous act because 
there 
are extremists in the United States who are already criticizing 
him for lifting the embargo against Vietnam. We also tell 
President Clinton that just as he was brave enough to lift the 
embargo on Vietnam, he must have the courage to lift the embargo 
on Cuba, because that is a real disgrace to the policy of U.S. 
leaders. [applause] [end recording] 
  The United States imposed the trade embargo on Vietnam in 
1975, when U.S. troops were defeated by the Vietnamese people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

