<H3> <TI>   U.S. Groups Begin Political Campaign To Lift Blockade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1002011394 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1002011394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, people opposing the U.S. blockade against 
Cuba are in Washington supporting a bill calling for the 
reestablishment of ties between the two countries. The support 
was organized by religious groups, scholars, and politicians to 
mark the beginning of a campaign against the aggressive U.S. 
policy toward Cuba. 
  The bill is entitled, Act for Free Trade With Cuba, and is 
sponsored by Democratic Representative Charles Rangel, who 
describes Washington's policy as hypocrital, given the current 
international conditions. However, in political circles in the 
United States, the climate is that of prudence in forecasting a 
victory in Congress because a change in policy toward Cuba 
depends to a degree on the Cuban-American community and Wall 
Street businesses. 

</TEXT>

