<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lage Meets Venezuelan Officials, Promotes Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902151894 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0000 GMT 9 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0902151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Cuban Vice President Carlos Lage this afternoon in 
Caracas reiterated Cuba's interest in promoting investment with 
Latin American capital. During his short visit to Caracas 
following an official six-day visit to Brazil and en route to 
Colombia, Lage met with Venezuelan Foreign Minister Miguel Angel 
Burelli Rivas and other authorities. 
  In statements to the media in Caracas, Carlos Lage said the 
accusations of human rights abuse in Cuba are unjustified and 
just a part of Washington's harassment policy against Cuba. 
  Upon commenting on the changes taking place on the island, 
the Cuban vice president said that his country does not intend 
to become capitalist but to adapt itself to world conditions and 
perfect its socialist model. 
  On 9 February Vice President Lage will begin an official 
two-day visit to Colombia on the invitation of President Cesar 
Gaviria, with whom he will meet in Santa Fe de Bogota, as well 
as with several ministers of Gaviria's administration and with 
representatives of the National Industrialists Association of 
Colombia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

