<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cardenista Front Symbolically Joins EZLN Struggle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902164094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1812 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0902164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 7 Feb (EFE) -- The Cardenist Front for 
National Reconstruction Party (PFCRN) has symbolically joined 
the armed revolt in Chiapas and begun a tough fight to discredit 
its opponents in the presidential campaign. 
  Rafael Aguilar Talamantes, PFCRN candidate to the Mexican 
presidency, announced that its "vote-sponsoring brigades" will 
mobilize this week wearing a "uniform" -- a ski cap and 
sweatshirt -- like members of the Zapatist National Liberation 
Army (EZLN) who rebelled on 1 January. 
  Fernando Pineda, national propaganda secretary, today 
explained to EFE that the ski cap will be "a symbol of peace, 
not of war." He added that it will be worn as a symbol of the 
Zapatist struggle for democracy and to demand a "no to weapons, 
yes to the ballot box." 
  The ski cap is the main garment worn by Zapatist leaders. 
Rebel leader "Subcommander Marcos" says he wears it to honor 
the Mexican culture of "keeping things under wraps" in which the 
name of the ruling party's presidential candidate is withheld. 
  "The PFCRN fully agrees with the Zapatists' demands. We have 
adopted their ten points for democracy and offered ourselves as 
the Zapatists' peaceful branch because we believe their demands 
are just," Pineda said. 
  The opposition party spokesman said its members hope 
violence 
will stop and that just solutions will be given to the people of 
Chiapas and Mexico, where, according to him, there are more than 
40 million poor people, meaning half the country's population. 
The way to prevent permanent instability in the country is to 
promote new, in-depth economic policies and to help the poorest 
people overcome their backwardness. 
  "We are going to emphasize this platform unity with the EZLN 
in our political campaign and guarantee that a political rather 
than military solution prevails on 21 August (presidential 
election day)". 
  Aguilar Talamantes was applauded by dozens of supporters 
wearing black and white ski caps on 6 February when he began his 
campaign in the capital. 
  During his electoral campaign, which began in January, 
Aguilar Talamantes harshly criticized another opposition 
presidential candidate, Cuahtemoc Cardenas of the Party of the 
Democratic Revolution (PRD), whom he describes as "lacking 
seriousness and ideological commitment." 
  Aguilar Talamantes has also criticized Diego Fernandez de 
Cevallos of the conservative National Action Party (PAN) for his 
"elitist" character because he wants politics for "groups of 
decent people without taking the poor into consideration." 
  The PFCRN, known as the Worker's Socialist party until 1986, 
proposes to end agricultural backwardness; to sponsor progress, 
democracy, and development; and to promote an in-depth 
reconstruction of the country's political and social life as 
guidelines for winning the presidency. 
  Nine parties will participate in the 21 August general 
elections, but only the ruling PRI (Institutional Revolutionary 
Party), PAN, and PRD are considered strong. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

