<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Contradicts U.S. Human Rights Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1002014894 Santiago Television Nacional de Chile Imagen 
Internacional in Spanish 0000 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1002014894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Television Nacional de Chile Imagen 
Internacional </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks recorded comments by </F>
Interior Minister Enrique Krauss] 
  [Text] Interior Minister Enrique Krauss said the crisis at 
the Copper Corporation, Codelco, has not stained the country's 
image abroad as Senate President Gabriel Valdes claimed in 
Valparaiso on 8 February. 
  "I do not believe the country's positive image abroad has 
been harmed. Undoubtedly the Codelco affair is significant and 
serious, but it is hardly fair to see it as some sort of 
collapse. It would be a gross exaggeration to do so. As I see 
it, Codelco is not broke and the country is operating normally." 
  Krauss categorically stated that no human rights have been 
violated in Chile, contrary to what a U.S. Department of State 
report has claimed. 
  "Human rights are most definitely respected in Chile. I do 
not believe that any Chilean or foreigner who truly knows how 
things are here could say that human rights are violated in 
Chile. Any resident of this country who may feel that his or 
somebody else's human rights have been violated is free to go to 
court." 
  Krauss explained that in any democratic state violations 
must 
be reported to the courts, not to the government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

