<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Over 1,000 Terrorists Indicted in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WT0005Z Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 1 Jan 94 p A4 </F>
<F P=103> 94WT0005Z </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL COMERCIO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] The Office of Attorney General convicted over 1,000 
terrorists in cases it handled this year, Daniel Espichan Tumay 
announced yesterday. The official also appealed to authorities 
not to let down their guard facing the subversive enemy so as to 
prevent such terrorists from once again sowing unrest among the 
people. 
  Espichan Tumay further noted that the respectable figure was 
achieved thanks to the excellent work of the Judicial Branch and 
military and reported that in 1993, 1,500 reformed terrorists 
had cooperated with the courts. 
  While observing that the Peruvian people are convinced that 
positive progress has been made in the fight, he repeated his 
appeal to civilian, military, and police authorities not to rest 
on their laurels. 
  "We must understand that terrorism will continue its 
onslaught because some leaders remain at large. Peace will be 
achieved only as the result of well-planned, transparent work 
and while paying respect to human rights," he said. 
<H5>  Presidential Instructions on Human Rights </H5>
  He also reported that as a special mission entrusted to him 
by President Alberto Fujimori, he has toured the country 
explaining to civil authorities and officials in the Judicial 
Branch and Attorney General's Office that they must take special 
precautions when apprehending individuals. 
  "The Police have been technically and scientifically trained 
and will find evidence proving whether or not a person is 
responsible for a crime. Otherwise, the rights of any citizen 
could be violated," he explained. 
  He said errors have been made in some cases and that the 
proper authorities have been duly notified, but added that what 
was important was "not to make any more." 
  Espichan Tumay said he is confident that with a titular 
Supreme Court, things will improve. 
  "A great deal remains to be done. We still have many 
prisoners who have been charged and all of Peru's higher courts 
must also be instructed to follow the same procedures applied in 
Lima," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32610 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat028_r_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-028 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

