<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Issues Declaration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902143694 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0902143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "Caracol's 0600 to 0900" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Cesar Gaviria's government has reaffirmed 
it has violated neither the letter nor spirit of the 
Constitution by authorizing the presence of foreign troops and 
aircraft in national territory. Following the decision by the 
Council of State--which is unconvinced by the president's 
explanations on the issue--a copy of which was sent to the 
Chamber of Representatives Commission to Investigate Charges and 
to the Attorney General's Office, the Presidential Palace issued 
the following declaration: 
  1. The Council of State, by saying the government's 
explanations government are unconvincing, has adopted an 
interpretation contrary to the traditional interpretation that 
has prevailed in the nation for the past 45 years. 
  2. Therefore, points 1,2, 3, 4, and 5 of the Council of 
State 
statement on the absence of permission from the Senate or a 
decision from the very council are the consequence of this new 
interpretation. Neither Senate permission nor a Council of 
State decision was requested, because it is considered we are 
dealing with international treaties that do not so require. 
  3. The government does not believe the president of the 
Republic has violated the letter or spirit of the Constitution. 
  4. The government has delivered to the media a copy of the 
letter the president of the Republic has sent to the Council of 
State in which the government cites what it considers a correct 
interpretation of the Constitution on the issue. 
  5. What the Constitution seeks to establish is a procedure 
for granting permits for the transit of foreign troops that have 
intentions of war against third nations. It does not seek 
whatsoever to regulate joint training operations, high-tech 
operations, equipment maintenance, or technical assistance that 
are part of international treaties in force. 
  6. The acceptance of the legal interpretation of the Council 
of State would end military-technical cooperation between 
Colombia and other nations, particularly cooperation on which 
Colombia has insisted so much in its struggle against 
drug-trafficking cartels. 
  7. Despite the Council of State's statement, this does not 
have a bearing on the validity of international treaties signed 
by Colombia, nor does it constitute a ruling or a sentence 
regarding the government's conduct on the issue. 
  The Narino Presidential Palace declaration concludes by 
stating President Cesar Gaviria is planning a news conference 
during which he will once again broach the touchy issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32617 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat028_o_94004" </HT>


