<H3> <TI>   Minister Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902131394 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0902131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "Caracol's 0600 to 0900" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota -- The national government stated 
moments ago the Council of State's opinion on the presence of 
foreign troops in our country does not obligate it to suspend or 
repeal the agreements signed by the Colombian Government in this 
regard. 
  Government Minister Fabio Villegas, the minister in charge 
of 
political issues, said the position voiced by the high-ranking 
tribunal [as heard] does not obligate the government to 
immediately withdraw the troops, which are in Juanchaco and 
which have created a serious controversy among various sectors 
of the country. 
  He insisted the Council of State did not issue a ruling, 
rather, an opinion that will now be debated at the Charges 
[Acusacion] Committee of the Chamber of Representatives and will 
be studied by the Attorney General's Office. 
  The Executive Branch stated in a communique the president of 
the Republic violated neither the letter nor spirit of the 
Constitution. The executive branch will not avoid the political 
debate at the Congress of the Republic. It is not our goal to 
deceive anyone, because the documents which contain these 
agreements have been at the Colombians' disposal, and thus, 
there is nothing secret, the government minister added. 

</TEXT>

