<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Notes Liberal, Conservative Election Campaigns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0902164194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0902164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Raul Gutierrez; from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Liberals have brought back the color red of times 
past in their publicity. Modern billboards with a cardinal 
bird, an attractive young woman, and seductive lips will 
persuade the electorate of the importance of voting for the 
Liberal Party candidates. Pedro Gomez was tasked with changing 
the party's image. 
  [Begin Gomez recording] The goal is to motivate those who 
are 
liberal to participate, as well as to make them remember the 
party's achievements. [end recording] 
  Beyond the red billboards, the Liberals have changed their 
old hymn and put modern music to their messages on voting, 
social welfare, and divorce. Things at the Conservative Party 
are different. The day after tomorrow, Andres Pastrana will 
make his presidential candidacy official, and the Conservative 
National Directorate [DCN] is working full steam ahead on the 
preparations for the 18 February convention, which will seek to 
draft a platform for the candidate, who undoubtedly will be 
Pastrana. 
  [Begin DCN member Cornelio Reyes recording] The name of 
Andres Pastrana is gaining more supporters as the party, its 
masses, and leaders are aware that he is the only viable, 
possible, and winning option. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

