<H3> <TI>   Police Increase Presence Around U.S. Interests Section </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202174194 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1641 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1202174194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 12 Feb (DPA) -- For the second consecutive 
day, the Cuban police today maintained surveillance around the 
U.S. Interests Section in Havana. On 11 February a group of 
people tried to enter the U.S. offices and incidents developed. 
  According to eyewitnesses, an unknown number of Cubans tried 
to enter the U.S. Interests Section offices in Havana and this 
resulted in the arrest of approximately 10 persons. The 
eyewitnesses reported that no one entered the U.S. offices and 
added that some people were injured in the attempt. 
  DPA reporters visited the site of the incident located on 
Havana's Caribbean seashore drive [Malecon], and saw that police 
surveillance had been heightened in the area. However, the 
situation is one of complete calm. 
  Members of the Cuban National Police are asking the people 
who have to pass through the area to do so quickly. They are 
also asking drivers not to park their vehicles in the area. 
Traffic is normal. 
  Persistent rumors spread in Havana on 10 February. The 
people were told that the U.S. Interests Section would approve 
visas for all Cuban citizens who requested them. A U.S. 
Interests Section spokesperson told DPA that these rumors are 
"totally and absolutely false" and that no Cuban citizen had 
entered the U.S. offices. 

</TEXT>

