<H3> <TI>   Effort To Undermine Exile Community Summit Causes Unrest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202230294 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 2140 GMT 12 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202230294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Program for the Mediterranean] </F>
  [Text] It has been reported that the Cuban Government 
could, next Tuesday, officially convene a conference of Cubans 
living abroad and in Cuba. These sources indicate that the 
meeting is planned for the end of April -- a meeting between 
members of the Cuban community living abroad and common citizens 
-- to discuss topics that are of interest to both sides in an 
effort to broaden current exchanges. 
  Representatives from the powerful Cuban-North American 
community will attend the meeting between Cubans, in addition to 
representatives from other Cuban communities living in Latin 
America, Europe, and other areas. 
  Meanwhile, ultraconservative sectors excluded from this 
meeting are doing everything in their power to stop it. To this 
end, they are using everything from threats against the 
participants to a intensive defamation propaganda campaign 
against the meeting. 
  In fact for the past 48 hours, radio stations broadcasting 
to 
Cuba from U.S. territory as well as television stations 
broadcasting from the United States which are received in 
Havana, have transmitted false reports, like the alleged closure 
of the U.S. Interests Office in Havana, to cause unrest among 
the people who go there everyday to wait for visas, which the 
U.S. State Department hands out sparingly as a way to encourage 
illegal departures. 
  This week, Radio Rebede reported from outside the U.S. 
Interests Office on the irritation of the people who wait in 
long lines for a visa they very seldom receive. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

