<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joseph on U.S. Request for Naming of New Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1102192294 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1102192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The United States has always played a dominant 
role in the search for a solution to the Haitian crisis. One 
cannot speak of interference, according to former Chamber of 
Deputies President Antoine Joseph, who considers it normal for 
the United States to request President Aristide to choose a new 
prime minister to fill the vacuum created by the departure of 
Prime Minister Robert Malval. Let us listen to Antoine Joseph: 
  [Begin recording, in Creole] What you call giving orders is 
what I see as the fact that the United States is now considered 
the world cop. Second, the United States is very strong in the 
United Nations and has played an important role in the Haitian 
crisis. If they can call that giving orders.... 
  Furthermore, the United States has given pretty substantial 
support to President Jean-Bertrand Aristide. It is true that 
there are difficulties preventing his physical return. 
Personally, I do not consider it a big deal that the United 
States, seeing that there is now an executive vacuum and that 
this vacuum is tempting, that this vacuum is a kind of bait, 
believes that the vacuum entails the sort of resolutions 
resulting from these national conferences. The United States may 
deem it necessary for the vacuum to be filled as soon as 
possible. It therefore asks President Aristide to name a prime 
minister so as to begin filling the executive vacuum. [end 
recording] 
  Furthermore, Antoine Joseph considers the resolution 
recently 
adopted by the employers' associations realistic. This 
resolution supports the main themes of the Governors Island 
agreement and of the New York pact. Joseph thinks the military 
considers the UN Mission in Haiti [MINUHA] a real slap. The 
MINUHA agreements can be revised by the Haitian parliament, 
according to Dr. Joseph, former president of the Chamber of 
Deputies. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

