<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Explosion Destroys Clandestine Fuel Warehouses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1302130694 Paris AFP in Spanish 0920 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1302130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 13 Jan [date as received] (AFP) -- 
Last night in Port-au-Prince a powerful explosion destroyed 
several clandestine fuel warehouses. An AFP correspondent 
reported on Sunday that the explosion claimed no victims. 
  The explosions and resulting fire were caused by an 
irresponsible smoker. Dozens of buildings were damaged, 
including a small 20-room hotel. 
  The fire had not yet been controlled this morning, six hours 
after the initial blast, which occurred when a tanker truck 
exploded. At the site, it was confirmed that firefighters have 
limited resources with which to work. 
  The petroleum products stored at the warehouses on Cesar 
Street, near the cathedral in the Haitian capital, had been 
brought in from the Dominican Republic. Gasoline sells for 22 
Haitian dollars ($7.5) [unit not given] on the black market. 
  The UN ordered an oil embargo against Haiti last October to 
pressure the military government which seized power in 1991 by 
overthrowing Jean Bertrand Aristide, the democratically elected 
president of Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

