<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRD Deputy: Zapatists Will Not Participate in Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102135994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1645 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1102135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 8 Feb (EFE) -- The opposition Party of 
the Democratic Revolution (PRD), the third political force in 
Mexico, asserted today that the Zapatist National Liberation 
Army (EZLN) will not become a political party. PRD Deputy 
Roberto Robles Garnica rejected the possibility that the rebels, 
who rose up in arms in Chiapas in southeastern Mexico, will 
participate in the presidential elections to be held on 21 
August 1994. 
  The deputy said he was pleased that a peasant movement had 
arisen in Chiapas because they are expressing what peasants 
throughout the country have been demanding for decades. He 
underscored that the armed conflict has made a significant 
change in Mexican politics. 
  Robles also stated that it has been said that the EZLN is 
only fighting for four small zones but that this is an attempt 
to oversimplify events, as it has been proven that their demands 
are the ones of all poor Indians and peasants. 
  Despite this, he insisted, it will be difficult for the EZLN 
to participate in the next federal elections, "because if they 
become a party it would a local one." However, Robles Garnica 
admitted that the Zapatist rebels could support one of the 
presidential candidates. He said, however, that he did not care 
to comment on how they could go about entering politics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

