<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chiapas Congress Approves Sanctions Against Torture </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1002132194 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0341 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1002132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez, 8 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- The Chiapas 
Congress today approved severe sanctions against torture and a 
tax exemption as part of the reconciliation process in Chiapas. 
This reconciliation process prompted an imminent peace meeting. 
  Congress President Juan Jose Rueda said the Law to Prevent 
and Punish Torture, which the state legislature approved, 
establishes sentences of one to 12 years imprisonment for 
committing torture. 
  Governor Javier Lopez Moreno sponsored the measure, which 
also invalidates confessions made in the absence of a defense 
lawyer and which is within a framework of pacification measures. 
These measures include an amnesty for common crimes committed 
during the conflict. 
  The local congress also approved a pardon of state taxes 
between January and June of 1994 in the 30 municipalities 
affected by the conflict, which began on 1 January with the 
emergence of the armed group the Zapatist National Liberation 
Army. 
  According to the measure adopted in Tuxtla Gutierrez, which 
is located 1,100 km southeast of Mexico City, taxpayers of the 
Lacandona Jungle and the Chiapas Highlands will be exempt from 
paying taxes on land, income [nomina], and unlisted businesses. 
  Governor Lopez Moreno has decided to reform the penal code 
following demands made by Indian leaders and farmers in Chiapas 
who have criticized this document by calling it the most 
"backward" in the country. 
  A virtual truce has prevailed in the conflict area since 12 
January, when President Carlos Salinas de Gortari decreed a 
unilateral cease-fire as a measure to facilitate actions by 
Peace Commissioner Manuel Camacho Solis. 
  Camacho Solis and the armed group are awaiting an "imminent" 
and first peace meeting aimed at finding a solution to the armed 
conflict, which, according to official figures, has resulted in 
many deaths. 
  Meanwhile, residents of the Teopisca, Huehuetan, Cacahoatan, 
Tuzantan, and Mapastepec Municipalities have occupied local 
governmental buildings to demand the dismissal of their 
respective mayors, whom they accuse of corruption and of 
promoting violence. 
  Teopisca residents on 8 February also blocked the 
Pan-American Highway between San Cristobal de las Casas and 
Comitan to call attention to their demand, which is similar to 
that of the residents of other municipalities located in the 
conflict area. 
  The demonstrators prevented the delivery of medicines, 
potable water, and food to the municipality, allowing only 
journalists to enter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

