<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Cross Has Contact With Former Chiapas State Governor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1302181794 Paris AFP in Spanish 1452 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1302181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Cristobal de Las Casas, 13 Feb (AFP) -- The Red 
Cross has had contact with retired General Absalon Castellanos, 
the former governor of the Mexican State of Chiapas, who has 
been a hostage of the rebels since 2 January. It is also 
believed that Castellanos will be released quite soon. 
  In a communique, the organization stated that, "following 
Red 
Cross International (IRC) criterion, IRC delegates were allowed 
to see the hostage, who sent a memento to his relatives." 
  Castellanos was abducted from his ranch by members of the 
Zapatist National Liberation Army (EZLN). The rebels "tried" 
him and sentenced him life in prison. That decision was later 
overturned. 
  The organization's communique added that "if an agreement 
regarding any hostage release can be reached, the IRC is ready 
to meet its commitment as a neutral intermediary." 
  A majority of people in San Cristobal believe that 
Castellanos will be released very soon. Some reports say that 
the event may even take place this very Sunday. 
  Other sources, however, say Castellanos will be freed after 
the first round of talks between the EZLN and the government. 
The place and date for the talks is still unknown, although it 
is believed that they may begin in the next few days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

