<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102173294 </F>
<F P=103> PA1102173294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the Mexican elections 
scheduled for 21 August 1994. 
  Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, presidential candidate of the 
Democratic 
Revolution Party (PRD), has received important support from the 
National Democratic Alliance today. The new electoral alliance 
is comprised by the center-left PRD and by more than 100 small 
political parties and social and people's organizations. 
(Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2105 GMT 5 Feb 94) 
  Cardenas, the PRD candidate, referred to a democracy and 
justice agreement signed by the eight political parties and 
their candidates. "What I want to tell you comrades about what 
we saw in these agreements is a possibility of free elections 
being held, a possibility for our democracy to progress; that is 
the only guarantee we have for peace in the nation," Cardenas 
said. He attended an ecologist forum organized by the PRD this 
morning. (Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 
5 Feb 94) 
  PRD candidate Cardenas has called on all the nation's 
political forces and the government during a political rally at 
the Revolutionary monument last weekend "to go from promises and 
words to concrete actions to guarantee honest elections on 21 
August." (Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in 
Spanish 1300 GMT 7 Feb 94) 
  Cardenas led a march entitled 100 Hours for Democracy in the 
Mexican capital today. During a news conference, the PRD 
candidate talked about the goal of the this march: "To summon 
officially a special congressional session to implement the 
necessary legislative reforms to guarantee the electoral 
authorities' impartiality," Cardenas stated. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 10 Feb 94) 
  Luis Donaldo Colosio, the PRI's (Institutional Revolutionary 
Party) official presidential candidate, proposed six basic 
points to guarantee impartial elections on 21 August today. He 
urged PRI members not to resort to methods that may damage the 
nation, thereby risking Mexicans' security. (Mexico City Canal 
13 Television Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 4 Feb 94) 
  PRI candidate Colosio, on the campaign trail in Mexico City 
during the commemoration of the Constitution's 70th anniversary, 
said the Constitution is a guarantee for civil coexistence. "I 
want to restate my conviction and loyalty to its ideals, 
aspirations. I firmly believe in individual rights consecrated 
in the Constitution. I believe deeply in its social orientation 
and valuable democratic contents," he commented. (Mexico City 
XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 5 Feb 94) 
  Colosio has made a commitment to work toward gaining 
convinced and reasoned votes in the coming elections. On the 
campaign trail in Mexico City, Colosio has invited the people to 
compare the PRI proposal with those of the other parties. 
(Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 
GMT 7 Feb 94) 
  PRI candidate Colosio has met with leaders of national 
teachers associations, saying public education is our 
sovereignty's source of vitality. Colosio has said: "I defend 
and will defend the lay and free characteristics of the 
education offered by the state." Subsequently, Colosio met with 
Broad Socialist-Leftist Party members led by Manuel Terrazas, 
who offered him their support. (Mexico City Canal 13 Television 
Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 8 Feb 94) 
  Colosio has acknowledged that an ostentatious campaign is an 
insult to the Mexican people; therefore, his will be austere. 
"I will continue with a simple, sober, broadly represented 
campaign in each and every community as we have been doing in 
those we have visited," he has said. (Mexico City Radio ACIR 
Network in spanish 0030 GMT 9 Feb 94) 
  On the campaign trail in Jalisco State, Colosio has made a 
commitment to lead a government of actions, not of words. "I 
have come to make a commitment before you, without demagogy, 
without simulations, or myths, because what you appreciate the 
most is the truth. You appreciate straightforward talk; that is 
the way you speak, and that is the way I want us to speak to 
each other," he has said. (Mexico City XEW Television Network 
in Spanish 0435 GMT 10 Feb 94) 
  Diego Fernandez de Cevallos, National Action Party (PAN) 
presidential candidate, has rejected the state as lord and 
master of the economy. Fernandez has said if he were elected 
president he would continue with the Solidarity Program, but he 
said he would strengthen municipal structures. He has spoken 
out for "a peaceful not a violent change in Mexico." (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 5 Feb 94) 
  Jorge Gonzalez Torres, presidential candidate for the 
Mexican 
Green Ecologist Party, has announced as of today his political 
campaign will be against NAFTA, as well as against the 
constitutional reforms, which will allow sons of foreigners to 
aspire to the Presidency after the year 2000. (Madrid EFE in 
Spanish 1803 GMT 7 Feb 94) 
  Marcela Lombarda Otero, Popular Socialist Party presidential 
candidate, has said during her tour in Zacatecas that to hold 
the coming elections peacefully, "Mexicans should be on guard, 
given the prevailing threats and pressures." (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 10 Feb 94) 
  Antonio Lozano Garcia, National Action Party secretary 
general, has said perfecting the electoral legal framework is 
fundamental to changing the nation's political reality. Lozano 
has said the PRI and government practices must be eliminated, 
given that until a clear division is made between the official 
party and the government, the democratic process cannot be 
achieved. (Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in 
Spanish 1300 GMT 4 Feb 94) 
  Pablo Emilio Madero, National Opposition Union (UNO) 
candidate, has said more important than reviewing electoral law 
is "the need to count on impartial authorities." (Mexico City 
Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 4 Feb 94) 
  UNO candidate Madero has told students of the Spanish 
American University more reforms are necessary to the electoral 
rulings to guarantee honest and democratic elections. Madero 
has said: "The conditions are set to allow for clean elections. 
There has been an undeniable opening in the media, something I 
have said before." (Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca 
Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 8 Feb 94) 
  During the last day of his campaign trail in Morelos, UNO 
candidate Madero held a meeting with party members at municipal 
headquarters. After traveling to Jocultal, he said election 
conditions had changed radically. He said the next step for 
Mexico "is to achieve democracy, as this is for the good of the 
nation. Let no one hesitate," he said, "because the good of the 
nation should be above any party interests." (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 10 Feb 94) 
  Cecilia Soto, presidential candidate for the Labor Party, 
has 
said if elected she will propose procedural changes to achieve 
justice in the nation, and she would reopen the Guadalajara gas 
explosion case, "as someone must be made responsible." "I have 
no possibilities of being elected if the nation and the 
elections develop without any significant," Soto has said. 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 10 Feb 
94) 

</TEXT>

