<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1002201094 </F>
<F P=103> PY1002201094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 10 
February: 
  The World Bank granted a $76 million loan to Uruguay to 
implement agricultural projects and promote industrial 
development. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 1 
Feb 94 p 8) 
  The gross foreign debt was $7.735 billion and the net 
foreign 
debt $2.242 billion through 30 September 1993. The gross foreign 
debt rose $38 million during the first nine months in 1993 as a 
result of the public sector's debt, which increased $68 million, 
and private debt, which dropped $30 million. The public sector's 
foreign debt totalled $7.095 billion. (Montevideo EL PAIS in 
Spanish 2 Feb 94 Market Indicators Supplement p 1) 
  The National Statistics Institute on 1 February reported 
that 
the consumer price index increased 3.41 percent in January 
compared with the previous month, bringing the inflation rate 
for the last 12 months to 51.99 percent. Housing registered the 
highest increase with 8.08 percent; food, 3.28 percent; and 
beverages, 1.2 percent. (Montevideo LA MANANA in Spanish 2 Feb 
94 p 40) 
  On 3 February, the Central Bank of Uruguay reported that its 
net foreign reserves, RIN, increased $22.4 million in January. 
The total RIN is now $1.2253 billion. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR 
ECONOMICO in Spanish 4 Feb 94 p 7) 

</TEXT>

