<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Rules Decree on Gas Price Increase Unconstitutional </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202002094 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 11 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202002094 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Court of Constitutional Guarantees, with five 
votes in favor and one opposed, declared the executive decree 
increasing gasoline prices unconstitutional and suspended it for 
fundamental reasons. The Court also submitted this resolution 
to the Supreme Court's Constitutional Court and ruled that it be 
published in the official gazette. 
  The gasoline price increase has sparked a great deal of 
protest in the country for the past several days. Every day the 
Ecuadoran people ask the president to reconsider his decision, 
but Sixto Duran-Ballen has said that he will not reconsider. 
After learning of the Court of Constitutional Guarantees' 
ruling, the president said that he will appeal the decision 
before the Supreme Court's Constitutional Court. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

