<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Data Collection Satellite Services Offered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1102152294 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
10 Feb 94 p A16 </F>

<F P=103> PY1102152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Julio Ottoboni] </F>
  [Text] Sao Jose dos Campos -- On the first anniversary of 
the launching of the Data Collection Satellite-1 (SCD-1), 
Science and Technology Minister Jose Israel Vargas and Marcio 
Nogueira Barbosa, the National Institute of Space Research 
(INPE) director, yesterday announced in Sao Jose dos Campos the 
expansion of Brazilian satellite services to Colombian, 
Ecuadoran, Peruvian, and Bolivian scientific organizations that 
have asked the INPE to install data collection station in their 
respective territories. 
  Minister Israel Vargas said the Brazilian Space Agency, 
which 
is civilian run, will by-pass the developed countries' boycott 
against Brazil on the transfer of sensitive technology. He 
commented: "Our program is for strictly peaceful purposes." 
  The minister believes the new service will enable Brazil to 
enter the low altitude communications satellite market. He 
said: "One of the agency's main tasks is a review of the entire 
Brazilian space program." 
  The Science and Technology Ministry has important space 
cooperation agreements with China and is looking into the 
possibility of a partnership with Argentina. 

</TEXT>

