<H3> <TI>   Continued Cease-Fire, Dialogue Urged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102231994 Managua Radio Corporacion in Spanish 2200 GMT 
11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1102231994 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Corporacion </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Five O'Clock Sharp" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The precarious peace -- the truce -- in northern 
Nicaragua is being endangered by a huge military deployment that 
is keeping mediators from contacting rebel commander Chacal 
[Jose Angel Talavera], the leader of the 3-80 Northern Front. 
In light of this situation, the National Assembly unanimously 
and with the presence of all deputies -- those of the National 
Opposition Union, the Center Bloc, and the Sandinist National 
Liberation Front -- called for an end to the massacre and for 
peace in the countryside once and for all. 
  Let us listen to the statement: 
  [Begin unidentified speaker recording] 1. The National 
Assembly, in view of the armed conflict in municipalities in the 
north, believes it is necessary to work for a peaceful solution 
to avoid the death of Nicaraguan people. 
  2. We urge the government to maintain the halt of military 
operations and to carry out all actions to facilitate and 
promote a direct dialogue that should contribute to the creation 
of situations suitable for a definitive demilitarization of 
irregular forces. 
  3. The National Assembly urges the irregular forces to put 
down their weapons and rejoin civilian life to contribute to 
peace and to the economic and social recovery of the 
municipalities affected by the war. 
  4. We urge the government to adopt the necessary measures to 
evacuate the wounded, care for them, and to respect the lives of 
the rebels. We also urge the government to make efforts to 
create jobs and to integrate the rebels into the productive 
process. 
  5. The National Assembly reiterates its commitment and 
support for the peace process and urges the country's various 
sectors to contribute to the overall objective of definitively 
ending the dramatic war in this country. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

