<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shining Path Faction Forms `People's Liberation Army' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202131894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1908 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1202131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 11 Feb (EFE) -- A Shining Path dissident 
faction which rejects the peace agreement proposed by Shining 
Path leader Abimael Guzman has formed the "People's Liberation 
Army" (EPL) [Ejercito Popular de Liberacion], Peruvian police 
reported today. A National Counterterrorism Directorate 
(Dincote) spokesman explained that the EPL has rejected Guzman's 
leadership and claims it is the authentic representative of 
Maoist communism in Peru. 
  Abimael Guzman, arrested in September 1992 and sentenced to 
life in prison, admitted the political and military defeat of 
his organization that took up arms in 1980 and asked Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori to negotiate a peace settlement. 
  According to the spokesman, the EPL leaders are: Alberto 
Ramirez Durand, alias "Comrade Feliciano;" Julio Cesar Mezzich; 
and a third leader whose identity is kept secret by government 
information services. 
  The schism in the Peruvian terrorist band was confirmed in 
documents found by police when they recently arrested a 10 EPL 
members in the San Juan de Lurigancho district in Lima. In the 
documents, the dissidents call Guzman and his followers, "the 
opportunist rightist line" of the Peruvian Communist Party, the 
official name of Shining Path. In other messages, previously 
confiscated in several Peruvian jails, it was also established 
that the Shining Path members who are loyal to their leader call 
the EPL "the leftist execution line," the police source added. 
  According to police, the arrest of the EPL terrorists has 
neutralized the terrorist offensive launched in Lima on 7 
February, when a car bomb exploded next to the Air Force 
headquarters and a bomb was placed next to an Army garrison. 
  The terrorists were arrested in the Cerro "Casablanca" area, 
where they had established a training camp for handling weapons 
and explosives. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

