<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liberal Presidential Hopeful on State Council Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102165194 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1102165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Colombian Liberal Party </F>
presidential hopeful Humberto de la Calle Lombana by Dario 
Arizmendi; from "Caracol's 0600-0900" newscast -- live] 
  [Text] [Arizmendi] Today we greet Dr. Humberto de la Calle 
Lombana, one of the Liberal Party's presidential hopefuls and a 
former government minister under President Cesar Gaviria. What 
is your position on the Council of State decision regarding the 
conduct of President Gaviria and the presence of U.S. troops in 
our country? Good morning, Dr. Humberto de la Calle. 
  [De la Calle] Good morning, Dario. I am pleased to greet 
you. 
  [Arizmendi] The same here, sir. 
  [De la Calle] I can tell you the following: I criticized the 
little school episode because it was poorly handled. I believe 
that what the country deserved was to be told the whole truth 
right away, however I also want to tell you that I do not agree 
with the decision Council of State decision because I do not 
believe the Constitution has been violated. I share the belief 
that an international treaty is being applied here. We are not 
talking about a wartime situation or the presence of foreign 
troops here but of joint maneuvers aimed at improving Colombia's 
response capabilities in the area of security and the fight 
against crime. I believe there is a precedent. All Latin 
American countries conduct these type of joint exercises. 
Colombia has been holding them for the past 30 or 40 years. I 
believe the Council of State decision endangers all possible 
military cooperation in matters of security and the fight 
against drug trafficking. 
  Among other things, we not only receive military support, 
but 
also judicial support. This excess of nationalism only benefits 
criminals, drug traffickers, and the guerrillas. I do not share 
the positions of the Council of State. 
  [Arizmendi] Dr. Humberto de la Calle Lombana, do you believe 
this decision made by the Council of State can seriously 
endanger the candidacy of President Cesar Gaviria for the post 
of OAS secretary general. 
  [De la Calle] I frankly hope the congress, which will review 
his conduct, will bear in mind what we have pointed out with the 
interpretation, which I believe is the correct one. I hope it 
will clear up this incident, which is naturally disturbing for 
the president and for Colombia. 

</TEXT>

