<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prosecutor General on President's Remarks on U.S. Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1002175194 Paris AFP in Spanish 1619 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1002175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Santa Fe de Bogota, 10 Feb (AFP) -- Colombian 
Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff said today he was surprised 
when President Cesar Gaviria said U.S. troops are in the country 
supporting the antidrug-trafficking struggle. De Greiff added 
he opposes this help. 
  De Greiff, known for his hard position against drug 
traffickers and the strongest persecutor of Pablo Escobar, the 
dead chief of the Medellin Cartel, said: "I do not believe we 
need the help of foreign troops to fight drug trafficking; we 
have done more than any other country to fight it and have never 
needed their help." 
  De Greiff also said he "had absolutely no idea" the U.S. 
soldiers were helping the Colombian Armed Forces in the 
antidrug-trafficking struggle. "I do not like to be lied to," 
the prosecutor general added. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

