<H3> <TI>   Gaviria Comments Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102020494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0040 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1102020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Live relay] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] Our reporter Dario Hoyos is talking with 
President Cesar Gaviria at the presidential building. Come in, 
Dario. 
  [Hoyos] President Gaviria, I can see you are very upset with 
the Council of State. In light of the ongoing political 
campaign, don't you think that this issue, which could turn into 
a confrontation between the executive and the judicial branches, 
will prove detrimental for the country? In addition, could it 
be that your election plans for the OAS are being thwarted? 
  [Gaviria] I will not discuss the last portion of your 
question. I know the State Council does not think along those 
lines. Anyway, we did not discuss it. I am concerned about 
what the Council of State did and the lack of specific legal 
documentation. If we were talking about a judicial ruling, it 
would be easier to study and consider the scope of what 
happened. But we are dealing with an opinion, a simple 
statement. I am not looking for trouble but I (?stick) to my 
convictions and do not allow myself to be intimidated by any 
decision or argument. I fight for the things I believe in. But 
I am not upset. I normally do not get upset, but my convictions 
are strong. What you are hearing indicates firmness of 
conviction. I think the legal arguments that we sent to the 
Council of State are valid. 

</TEXT>

