<H3> <TI>   Says Debate on Troops `Over' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202015294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202015294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alvaro Ayala] </F>
  [Text] During a ceremony in which Police Director General 
Octavio Vargas Silva submitted the final report on the 
modernization of his organization, President Cesar Gaviria took 
the opportunity to say he never intended to offend the State 
Council. He then said he considers the debate generated by the 
presence of U.S. troops in Juanchaco Ladrilleros and Bahia 
Malaga to be over and done with. 
  [Begin Gaviria recording] Yes, undoubtedly, in the wake of 
the State Council's statement yesterday, what could be called a 
controversy has now ended. I did not intend to offend the State 
Council, and I do not believe I did offend the council. What I 
did was defend a legal position -- an interpretation of the 
Constitution -- and to respect Colombia's international treaties 
and their development, which I consider essential. I consider 
this essential not for the president or his position, but for 
the professionalization of the Armed Forces and for 
international cooperation in efforts to counter drug 
trafficking. [end recording] 
  During the same ceremony, former Police Director General 
Miguel Antonio Gomez Padilla for the first time appeared in 
public wearing civilian clothes. 

</TEXT>

