<H3> <TI>   Minister: Cali Cartel Promoted U.S. Troop Controversy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202020394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202020394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Miriam Ortiz from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Defense Minister Rafael Pardo has reiterated that 
the Cali Cartel has promoted the campaign against the presence 
of U.S. troops on the Pacific coast to keep them out of the 
country. Miriam Ortiz has the report. 
  In his latest speeches, President Cesar Gaviria always 
linked 
the Cali Cartel to the controversy over the presence of U.S. 
military personnel in Juanchaco. 
  The defense minister today reiterated his position, which 
many people are now viewing as plausible. 
  [Begin Pardo recording] When the whole thing began, we 
noticed that drug traffickers were interested in some aspects of 
this scandal. I also think that the debate has had its own 
dynamics, and in many cases it is also a product of some 
people's deep-rooted ideas. We are not discarding the 
possibility that some sectors linked to drug trafficking are 
interested in this situation. [end recording] 
  Pardo also said that as long as applicable international 
agreements are in effect, U.S. troops will continue to come to 
Colombia. 

</TEXT>

