<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comptroller Reports Mismanagement of Public Funds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1102194794 Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO SIGLO in Spanish 5 
Feb 94 pp 1A, 1B </F>

<F P=103> PA1102194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO SIGLO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Comptroller General Manuel Francisco Becerra 
Barney has issued one of the most important reports on 
corruption in the country, by pointing out serious 
irregularities and mismanagement of public funds in nearly 100 
state institutions. 
  In a report issued to Congress and also sent to President 
Cesar Gaviria, the comptroller indicated that the 
Comptrollership's Fiscal Investigations and Trials Directorate 
has detected approximately 40 billion pesos worth of shortages 
that have not been reimbursed. Of that amount, 27.5 billion 
pesos correspond to public institutions and the central 
government sector and the rest to government-private capital 
enterprises and to state-owned industrial and commercial 
enterprises. 
  The comptroller also indicated that his office will do 
everything possible to seize the assets of 1,100 officials who 
committed irregularities in handling funds. The report also 
demanded that those officials present themselves to the Treasury 
to return the funds before the appropriate authorities intervene. 
  The institutions mentioned include several ministries and 
administrative departments. The most often mentioned ministries 
are defense, health, education, and finance. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

