<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Outlines Coupists' Options to President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1202034394 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1202034394 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cecilia Pachano from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today, Defense Minister Rafael Angel Montero Revette 
met with the president and submitted a report on the officers 
currently being tried in connection with the 4 February and 27 
November events so the president can study the information and 
make his final decision concerning a possible stay of 
proceedings. 
  General Montero Revette confirmed he met with the prisoners 
yesterday at the San Carlos Barracks. He said the goal was to 
explain why they are not compelled to request their release, 
adding that this decision could be adopted at will. He also said 
the government has pledged to give them scholarships and 
employment so they may quickly become part of society. The 
scholarships and employment will be given based on their rank 
and work areas. 
  The defense minister confirmed that Yare Prison's military 
annex was definitely closed down; he added that the officers 
being tried in connection with the 27 November and 4 February 
events will not be transferred to Ramo Verde. 

</TEXT>

