<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Newspaper `Explains' U.S. Interests Section Events </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1402001894 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 2100 GMT 
13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1402001894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An article in today's JUVENTUD REBELDE newspaper 
explains the events that occured in the vicinity of the U.S. 
Interests Section in Havana over the past three days, after the 
counterrevolution launched rumors that the Cuban security guards 
had been withdrawn. The item claims that Miami 
counterrevolutionary organizations and special services of 
imperialism are wholly responsible for the incidents that 
occurred on 10 and 11 February. 
  They had tried to create a massive influx of Cuban citizens 
to the U.S. Interests Section as a way to denigrate the 
Revolution and create an incident that would further damage the 
nonexistent relations between the two countries. The paper 
points out that to do this, they used the rumor technique, 
spreading false reports that the Cuban Government was interested 
in encouraging an event of that nature. 
  JUVENTUD REBELDE says: The rumors began on the morning of 10 
February when the counterrevolution began to spread the news 
that the sentries had been withdrawn, and that the U.S. 
Interests Section was expeditiously issuing visas to anyone 
applying for them at the U.S. Interests Section. 
  During all [several seconds lost due to tape change] from 
Centro Habana [Municipality] and from the Cojimar neighborhood 
expressed their intentions of going to the place, while others 
went to the U.S. Interests Section. Those people were joined by 
a number of residents from Arroyo Naranjo Municipality. 
  On 11 February, the internal forces of order cordoned off 
the 
streets that provided access to the U.S. Interests Section to 
prevent the crowds from getting near the Section offices. At 
around noon on Friday [11 February], according to JUVENTUD 
REBELDE, the presence of lumpen in the area was obvious, again 
showing that this is the natural medium from which the 
counterrevolution draws its sustenance. 
  During the course of the incidents at the U.S. Interests 
Section, 82 people were identified and detained for a few hours. 
At present, a number of citizens are still under arrest, and the 
instigators of the events are being identified. 
  In its Sunday item, JUVENTUD REBELDE reports that several 
participants in the incidents said they heard rumors from Miami 
radio stations that visas would be freely granted. 
  It is obvious who masterminded the incidents at the U.S. 
Interests Section. This is how the mechanisms of the 
counterrevolution and imperialism operate -- on the basis of 
deception and cynicism. Responsibility for what has happened 
belongs wholly and exclusively to imperialism, to the 
counterrevolutionaries in Miami, and to the agitators disguised 
as dissidents. Cuba does not practice policies based on force. 
The force of Cuba's policy lies in its proverbial justice, 
crystal clarity, and fidelity to its proclaimed principles, 
according to today's article in JUVENTUD REBELDE, entitled, 
"What Happened at the U.S. Interests Section?" 
  The embassies in Cuba will always be able to count on the 
protection and facilities they need to carry out their tasks and 
ensure the the security of their members. Nothing happened 
inside the U.S. Interests Section. There are no Cuban citizens 
inside the offices. No one was hurt or injured. Once the rumor 
about free issuance of visas was denied, everything returned to 
normal. 
  Nevertheless, JUVENTUD REBELDE adds, these kinds of 
incidents 
and this type of irresponsibility have the potential to provoke 
more serious consequences. The onus falls entirely on whoever is 
responsible for promoting this kind of thing. Let this incident 
serve as an experience for the unscrupulous authors of this 
escapade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

