<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Says Cuba Willing To Reenter OAS </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402223694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1547 GMT 13 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1402223694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 13 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- Cuban Ambassador to 
Uruguay Abelardo Curbelo Padron has said Cuba would be willing 
to reenter the OAS -- it was expelled in 1962 -- if this action 
will foster regional integration and reduce tension in the 
continent. 
  The diplomat, who was appointed to represent his country in 
Mexico, told LA REPUBLICA newspaper that "Cuba is willing to 
consider the issue if the OAS asks for the island's reentry. [no 
closing quotation marks as published] 
  "Cuba was arbitrarily removed from the OAS and now the 
decision for its reentry is the organization's problem, not 
ours," the ambassador stated. He added that the international 
political situation has changed so much "that many people 
believe the decision to exclude Cuba is going out of fashion." 
  Curbelo said integration "was an old historic aspiration of 
the continent," and that the regional and subregional advances 
in this direction were "interesting." He noted: "For us, the 
integration process and the international meetings have an 
effective and practical value because, regarding the Caribbean's 
participation, they foster rapprochement of all countries." 
  Cuba, he added, does not participate in any regional 
integration process but has made important steps in this 
direction through the Caribbean Common Market. Therefore, he 
said, the experience gathered at the Latin American Integration 
Association will be important in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

