<F P=100> EL SALVADOR </F>
<H3> <TI>   Onusal Chief Says FMLN Demobilized `Long Time Ago' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402225294 San Salvador DIARIO LATINO in Spanish 11 Feb 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PA1402225294 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador DIARIO LATINO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "The FMLN [Farabundo Marti National Liberation 
Front] was demobilized a long time ago," said Onusal [UN 
Observers for El Salvador] chief Augusto Ramirez Ocampo when 
commenting on General Mauricio Ernesto Vargas' statements that 
the FMLN was still armed. 
  Vargas, a member of the government commission that signed 
the 
peace accords, reportedly said yesterday there are FMLN groups 
that have yet to be demobilized. 
  "Vargas is misinformed," Ocampo said, adding "he (Vargas) 
was 
a witness" of the FMLN's total demobilization, which the United 
Nations has also affirmed. 
  He recalled that the FMLN's structure was dismantled in 
August 1993 and that FMLN leaders rejected any responsibility 
for weapons found in the future. 
  Ocampo said "everyone is protected by the law" now, and 
sanctions will be enforced against those who violate it. 
  Referring to human rights supervision in El Salvador, he 
said 
"this is the most supervised country in the world as far as 
human rights are concerned," adding there are three operations 
underway: a permanent operation by the Onusal Human Rights 
Division, an independent observer, and one operation by the 
Human Rights Commission, which has its headquarters in Geneva. 
  He said the human rights situation "has achieved 
extraordinary progress." Ocampo made those statements after 
signing as a witness the 12th gentlemen's pact signed by 
representatives of the political parties that participate in the 
electoral process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

