<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombians Accused of Smuggling Fish to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1202155594 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 10 
Feb 94 Section 3 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PY1202155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Andre Lozano from Manaus Bureau] </F>
  [Text] The Coordinating Board of Brazilian Amazon Region 
Indian Organizations (Coiab) and the Ibama [Brazilian Institute 
for the Environment and Renewable Natural Resources] have 
accused Colombians of fostering the smuggling of fish out of the 
Amazon region into the United States. Both agencies estimate 
that returns on the illegal business with alevins (newly-hatched 
fish) amount to $2.4 million per week. 
  The Pastoral for Indigenous Communities of the Upper 
Solimoes 
contends that former members of the gang of Colombian drug 
kingpin Pablo Escobar, who died recently, might be members of 
the band of fish smugglers. 
  According to Father Joseney Lira, the Colombians leave their 
country through the city of Leticia, enter Brazil through 
Tabatinga, and go to the cities of Atalaia do Norte and Benjamin 
Constant, Amazonas State, using the Javari River. Lira said: 
"Most smuggling occurs in these two municipal districts. The 
Colombians purchase alevins at puny prices and resell them for 
600 real cruzeiros each." 
  The smuggled fish reportedly enter Colombia through Leticia, 
are flown by airplane to Bogota, and then to Miami (United 
States of America). Amazonas PF [federal police] Superintendent 
Mauro Sposito said the smuggled fish are also used to camouflage 
cocaine shipments from Leticia to the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32810 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat031_m_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-031 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

