<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defends Antiterrorist Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1502031094 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2055 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1502031094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 14 Feb (DPA) -- Today in Santa 
Fe de Bogota at the start of a three-day official visit to 
Colombia, Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori defended his 
government's measures to fight the "Shining Path" terrorist 
group. Fujimori, in brief statements to the press, said his 
country could no longer tolerate attacks by the fundamentalist 
Maoist group; therefore he implemented severe measures, like the 
so-called "self-coup" in April 1992, when he dissolved Congress 
and assumed extraordinary powers. 
  "What country in the world would accept 25,000 deaths 
(number 
of victims caused by political violence in Peru since 1980)? No 
developed country would have allowed this. That is why we took 
the appropriate measures; some of them were tough, but 
effective," the president said. 
  The Peruvian president, who arrived in Santa Fe de Bogota 
this morning and met at noon with his Colombian colleague Cesar 
Gaviria, said his visit shows the good relations between the two 
countries. 
  According to Narino House sources, Gaviria and Fujimori 
discussed basic topics like the fight against the 
drug-trafficking mafia and communist guerrilla groups, as well 
as the results of the Peruvian-Colombian Joint Commission to 
protect the Amazon jungle at their first meeting. 
  After speaking with Gaviria, Fujimori met for a few minutes 
with Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin and laid a wreath at the 
statue of Liberator Simon Bolivar, located in the historic 
central plaza surrounded by the Congress and Bogota's main 
Cathedral. 
  Tomorrow, Fujimori will explain to Colombian businessmen the 
measures he has adopted to internationalize the Peruvian economy 
to attract foreign capital. 
  Fujimori arrived in Colombia accompanied by Prime Minister 
Alfonso Bustamante, Foreign Minister Efrain Goldenberg, Health 
Minister Jaime Freundt-Thurne, Fisheries Minister Jaime Sobero, 
and several ruling party congressmen and businessmen. 

</TEXT>

