<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vows `No More Terrorism' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402231194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2112 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1402231194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 14 Feb (EFE) -- Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori said today in Santa Fe de Bogota that 
by the end of his term there will be no more terrorism in Peru, 
because he will wipe it out. 
  "Two of the world's most violent terrorist groups are being 
defeated, and by the end of my term they will no longer exist," 
Fujimori said, referring to the Shining Path [SL] and the Tupac 
Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA). 
  Fujimori, who began a two-day official visit to Colombia 
today, made the statement to journalists at the end of his first 
meeting with Colombian President Cesar Gaviria. 
  According to the Peruvian president, terrorism and 
subversive 
violence have claimed 25,000 lives in Peru. 
  He asked jokingly: "What has been the meaning of `Emperor' 
Fujimori's government?" He replied that his government "is 
defeating" the violent groups. 
  Fujimori reiterated by the time his constitutional terms 
ends 
"neither the SL nor the MRTA will exist in Peru. I am going to 
wipe them out." 
  Fujimori and Gaviria discussed during their first meeting 
topics such as drug trafficking and guerrillas, topics that 
affect both countries. They also discussed bilateral relations. 
  Both leaders will lay the groundwork for the creation of a 
Binational Neighbor Commission, and tomorrow they will sign a 
joint declaration in which they will announce new mechanisms of 
cooperation for the struggle against drug trafficking and 
guerrillas. 

</TEXT>

