<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   SEMANA Reports Prosecutor Negotiating Independently With 
Cali Cartel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402221394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1402221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The magazine SEMANA reported today that Prosecutor 
General Gustavo de Greiff, acting on his own and without 
consulting anyone, has been negotiating for more than a month 
with the Cali Cartel. According to the publication, the document 
signed by De Greiff reportedly gave a kind of safe-conduct pass 
to alleged Cali and Tulua drug traffickers to keep them from 
being arrested. The names of these drug traffickers are 
well-known figure Pacho Herrera, Jose Olmedo Campo, and a man 
named Renteria. According to the magazine, the passes would 
clearly show Prosecutor De Greiff has been in direct contact 
with Cali Cartel leaders for more than a month, without 
previously consulting the government or informing the security 
corps or the Attorney General's Office. SEMANA said a top 
government source expressed the government's surprise about the 
actions taken individually and privately by the prosecutor, 
because late last year the government and this office agreed to 
keep each other informed of any developments. 
  According to SEMANA, the serious thing about the case is not 
the fact that the prosecutor is acting like a loose cannon, but 
that from the moment when the drug traffickers first came to his 
office -- on 14 January -- it marked the beginning of the 
preliminary investigations. In other words, this marked the 
beginning of the search for evidence that must be provided by 
the DAS [Administrative Department of Security], the Dijin 
[Judicial Police and Investigations Directorate] in Colombia, 
and Interpol. The odd thing is that the Prosecutor General's 
Office did not officially inform any of these organizations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

